Architecture 

# 🏗️ Architecture Design - Distributed Rate Limiter System

## 📌 Overview

This document explains the high-level architecture of the Distributed Rate Limiter system designed to handle millions of requests with low latency and high availability.

The system ensures that API requests are controlled using the Token Bucket algorithm while maintaining scalability.

---

# 🌐 High-Level Architecture Flow

Client  
   ↓  
API Gateway / Load Balancer  
   ↓  
Rate Limiter Service  
   ↓  
Redis Cluster (Distributed Cache)  
   ↓  
Application Servers  

Monitoring & Logging System connected to Redis and App Servers.

---

# 🧩 Components Explained

## 1️⃣ Client

- Sends API requests
- Could be web app, mobile app, or third-party service
- Each request contains user ID or API key

---

## 2️⃣ API Gateway / Load Balancer

- Distributes traffic across multiple application servers
- Performs basic authentication validation
- Handles SSL termination
- Prevents direct exposure of internal services

Examples:
- Nginx
- Kong
- AWS API Gateway

---

## 3️⃣ Rate Limiter Service

Core logic layer.

Responsibilities:
- Checks if user has available tokens
- Applies Token Bucket algorithm
- Communicates with Redis
- Returns:
  - 200 → Allowed
  - 429 → Too Many Requests

This layer should be:
- Stateless
- Horizontally scalable
- Fast (<10ms overhead)

---

## 4️⃣ Redis Cluster (Distributed Cache)

Why Redis?

- Extremely fast in-memory storage
- Atomic increment operations
- Built-in TTL (Time to Live)
- Suitable for distributed systems

Stores:
- User token count
- Last refill timestamp

